the assumptions weakened to $\gcd(n_1, n_2)\leq 2$ and $\gcd(m_1, m_2)\leq 2$.  Schinzel~\cite{S12} characterized when this equation, with no assumptions on the greatest common denominators of $n_i$'s and $m_i$'s, but with $K={\mathbb{Q}}$ and $\mathcal{O}_K={\mathbb{Z}}$, has infinitely many solutions with a bounded denominator.




